-- Rebar Near Three-Month High on Expectation of Surging Demand
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2013-07-24T03:21:29Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-24/rebar-near-three-month-high-on-expectation-of-surging-demand.html
Steel reinforcement-bar futures in
Shanghai traded near the highest level in three months on
expectations consumption is outpacing supply as production slows.  Rebar for delivery in January on the Shanghai Futures
Exchange gained as much as 0.5 percent to 3,708  yuan  ($604) a
metric ton and was at 3,693 yuan at 10:53 a.m. in Beijing.
Futures climbed to 3,712 yuan on July 19, the highest level
since April 22.  Sichuan Expressway Co., an operator of toll roads, bridges
and tunnels in China, agreed to invest about 50 billion yuan
($8.1 billion) in infrastructure projects, it said in a filing
to Hong Kong’s stock exchange yesterday. China will accelerate
cutting overcapacity, according to a statement today by the
Ministry of Industry and  Information Technology , which placed
iron and steel on top of the list.  “Strengthening spot prices and falling inventory indicated
fixed asset investments are pretty strong,” Xia Junyan, analyst
at Wanda Futures Co., said from  Shanghai . “The phasing out of
smaller plants will help reduce supply,” he said.  Iron ore  for immediate delivery at Tianjin port rose 0.3
percent to $131.90 a ton yesterday, according to The Steel Index
Ltd. The average  spot price  for rebar rose 0.1 percent to 3,457
yuan yesterday, the highest since May, according to data from
Beijing Antaike Information Development Co.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
